      <hedline>
        <hl1>No State Income Tax for Teachers? Not So Fast</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Elizabeth Marquardt says proposal by Gov Gray Davis of California to exempt teachers from state income tax would prompt other public servants to seeking same exemption, and foster resentment between the professions; says teachers should be lured with other benefits and taxes should be left alone</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The proposal by Gov. Gray Davis of California to exempt teachers from the state income tax in an effort to increase teacher recruitment (front page, May 14) is misguided.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The proposal by Gov. Gray Davis of California to exempt teachers from the state income tax in an effort to increase teacher recruitment (front page, May 14) is misguided.</p>
        <p>If teachers receive an income tax exemption, what is to prevent public health nurses from demanding the same? Or other state workers? Or anyone else?</p>
        <p>The proposal runs the risk of creating a two-tiered structure of those who pay taxes and those who don't. That would hinder the state's ability to cover its budget and fosters resentment between the professions.</p>
        <p>Lure the teachers with other benefits, but keep their tax bill the same.</p>
        <p>ELIZABETH MARQUARDT  Waterville, Me., May 15, 2000</p>
      </block>
